The actual proof is quite involved because it needs to handle all possible cases of `xs` and `ys`, which can vary greatly in structure. The use of `aesop` and `omega` helps automate some of the simpler steps, but careful case distinctions are necessary to ensure correctness. This approach also ensures that all possible configurations of `xs` and `ys` are covered, without missing any edge cases.

